# ast-index Search Rules

Use `ast-index` first for codebase navigation tasks: finding files, symbols,
classes, usages, implementations, callers, outlines, module dependencies, and
project maps.

Before the first query in a project, run `ast-index stats`. If there is no
usable index yet, run `ast-index rebuild` from the project root. For large
repositories, prefer a scoped rebuild with `--include` or work from the
smallest relevant project root.

Do not run grep or broad text search after `ast-index` returns sufficient
structural results. Fall back to text search only for regex searches, string
literals, comments, or when `ast-index` returns no useful result.

Useful commands:

```bash
ast-index search "Query"
ast-index file "FileName"
ast-index symbol "SymbolName"
ast-index class "ClassName"
ast-index usages "SymbolName"
ast-index implementations "InterfaceOrBaseClass"
ast-index refs "SymbolName"
ast-index outline "path/to/File.kt"
ast-index map --limit 20
ast-index conventions
```

For monorepos with a trusted parent index, use `ast-index --walk-up ...` or
`AST_INDEX_WALK_UP=1`. Otherwise stay scoped to the nearest project root to
avoid mixing unrelated results.
